  <h2>El Dorado: Historic Small City with Aging Housing Stock</h2>
  <p>El Dorado is 30 miles east of Wichita, the Butler County seat. It's got real history — oil and refinery heritage, the Kansas Oil Museum, El Dorado Lake recreation. Population around 13,000, small-city feel with character. But that history also means the housing stock is older. Most homes are 1910s-1950s, solid construction but dated, sitting in the $80k-$180k range. It's more rural-feeling than the suburbs closer to Wichita, but people still commute here for Boeing and Koch Industries work.</p>
  <p>El Dorado homeowners are often longtime residents aging in place, heirs inheriting properties from parents who lived there 40-50 years, or people relocating to Wichita for work who need to move their El Dorado home fast.</p>

  <h2>El Dorado Housing Market: Older Homes, Lower Price Points</h2>
  <p>El Dorado's market is straightforward. Older homes, lower prices. You're looking at $80k-$180k typically. Most of the housing stock is 1910s-1950s construction — solid brick, good foundations, but aging systems and outdated layouts. The downtown historic district has character homes. The eastside is more residential. Nothing new or fancy, just real homes that have served families for generations.</p>
  <p>Because prices are lower and the market's quieter than Wichita proper, these homes can sit a long time on traditional listings. But the bones are good and prices are fair. That's why I buy here.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in El Dorado</h2>
  <p>Longtime El Dorado residents ready to downsize or retire out of Kansas. Estate sales from parents who owned the same house 40 years. Heirs inheriting property they don't want to manage from out of state. People relocating to Wichita for work who need to sell El Dorado property fast. Property owners with distressed or difficult situations — foreclosure, liens, deferred maintenance nobody wants to fix. Small-town folks who just want simple, clean exits without the hassle of six-month listings.</p>

